A unique and challenging take on tower defense. Basically a combination of tower defense + RTS. The controls can be difficult at times, and some of the strategies aren't immediately obvious. Some of the maps are trivially easy and some seem really hard. You can get most of the upgrades you need without making any microtransactions. A few vehicles are an insane amount of currency but you don't need any of them to clear the game. I wish the difficult curve was a little smoother but overall it's a satisfying game.

A really excellent single-player RTS. My only gripe is with the controls; 
the game is complex enough that just the touch screen is limiting. I'd like 
it if there were a separate camera mode, where I could precisely adjust the 
camera with on-screen controls and then lock it, because I find it hard to 
get exactly what I want from the multi-touch camera controls and I hate 
when I move the camera by accident. I'd also appreciate better ways to 
precisely position troops, like the ability to zoom closer or some AI for 
the troops so they'll squeeze together in cover automatically. It's a 
little frustrating trying to position one unit next to another and 
repeatedly selecting the second unit instead.

Looks like it would be fun, and the reviews are pretty good. However, the tutorial is garbage. I was put in a game with zero information, and had to figure some things out myself, when a few minutes later (that is, after a group of zombies attacked my base, I figured out how to create and move units, and uncovered two groups of zombies in nearby houses) and dialog comes up that teaches me how to move units. The dialog should've popped immediately as the game started, not as the first three groups of enemies have already killed my units. I kept playing for about half an hour, got tired of not knowing what I'm doing, and uninstalled.  While playing, I felt that the controls were very finicky: I'd tap on a unit and select the zombie next to it. I'd also appreciate information about the units, as in the first mission there are three (I think? It never really explained what to do) units I can make. The truck is obviously a truck, but I couldn't tell the difference between the two infantry units, so I just stuck with the less expensive one, since I also didn't know how to increase resource production (or even if that's possible).  I got it while it was on sale, so I didn't pay any money, which I'm glad about, because I'm very disappointed in what looked like a very fun game.

Played a few levels in and happily spent money on the IAPs to give the game a fair crack. Initially found the gameplay fun and original however was eventually let down by the extremely poor balancing.  After the first couple of levels the boosted resource start is pretty much required for even a fighting chance of reaching day 31 on even casual difficulty. Resources are frustratingly scare even with aggressive expansion.  Zombies scale over the course of a battle making unit upgrades essential to keep pace damagewise. However this causes repair costs to ramp up disproportionately to the survivability of your units which typically remain relatively squishy until max levelled.  This is made worse by the AI which requires constant babysitting to stop units blindly shooting at the closest enemy regardless of weapon type.  The enemy in contrast will make a beeline for your most valuable and fragile units, usually ignoring any defenders in the way. Whereas some of your units can miss, it seems enemy fire cannot be dodged which is unfortunate, since upgraded spitters in particular seem to have a habit of simply sniping out the RPG and tanks meant to stop them.

Fun game with a smart use of graphic. If this is an indie game made by a few persons, then the design team is smart indeed. Graphic is the most stunning here. Not because it is grand or realistic, but the design using simple geometry and transparency give the game a tactical impression. Units are represented by symbol. This enhance the impression even more. Control is good enough. Not perfect. I accidentally order unit to walk often. That means the control requires some learning to get used to. The weakest, though, seems to be audio. Music is great. Effect is ok. But it is obviously can be better. Imagine your units reporting contact. Your engineering screaming when parameters are breached. Some random radio sis from survivors. These sounds would have increased the feeling of urgency, a boon to this kind of game.

content: The overall game concept and system is sound but the difficulty can painfully crush your morale at points. Found out multiple times that you can be fine up to a point, then the next wave your units are suddenly dropping like flies and you might as well give up because recovery can be nigh impossible since your unit limit/upkeep, whatever you call it, drops with every unit lost. Thats my main issue. Also, the wonky-ish controls/ camera, overly long building capture for some, overly high unit cost/ upgrades.

Good game honestly. Problems: 1.  hard to move units around the map.   1a.  Frequently have issues trying to move a new unit into a stack of units.   1b.  4 or 5 times a game I am trying to select a unit or building, but I move a unit that I didn't realize I had selected, then I have problem 1a again.  2.  Does not support pen input, specifically nabi dreamtab pen or Samsung note spen.  Literally does not register any activity from the pen  3.  Not enough / no documentation.   3a.  Engineers apparently double the output of certain buildings, but after 5 or 6 hours playing I had to read it on Google to know. 3b.  Units are described as "good" at "killing X" but no way to quantify what "good" means.   3c.  Units are researchable based on a point system, but how do you know what unit to buy if you don't know how good it is (see 3b)  4.  To take over a large building (after clearing it out), it can take literally 13 minutes with a solider, or 6.5 minutes with a scout.  Multiple troops lower this time, but its still painfully slow.  Clearing one building may require clearing nearby buildings so you can station troops defensively to survive multiple "waves" during the wait.
